# Environment template for agentic-test-automation.
#
# Usage:
#   1. cp .env.example .env
#   2. Fill in each section below (section headers say which script consumes them).
#   3. Run scripts/step0_verify_tool_calling.py, step0b_verify_embeddings.py, step0c_xray_flavor.py.
#
# Never commit .env — it is in .gitignore. Only this template (.env.example) is tracked.

# ─── mTLS client certificate (uncomment if your gateway requires it) ─
# Most common: a single PKCS#12 bundle (.p12 OR .pfx — same format,
# different file extension) password-protected by IT. .pfx and .p12 are
# interchangeable, MTLS_PKCS12_FILE accepts either.
# MTLS_PKCS12_FILE=/absolute/path/to/client.pfx
# MTLS_PKCS12_PASSWORD=
#
# Alternative: separate PEM files for cert + key.
# MTLS_CERT_FILE=/absolute/path/to/client-cert.pem
# MTLS_KEY_FILE=/absolute/path/to/client-key.pem
# MTLS_KEY_PASSWORD=                              # only if the key is encrypted
#
# Server-side trust: only needed if the gateway/Jira/GitLab use a private CA not in
# certifi's default bundle. Most cloud-hosted gateways DON'T need this.
# SSL_CERT_FILE is read by httpx (the gateway client); REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE is read by
# requests (the Xray + GitLab clients). Set BOTH to the same bundle when using a
# private CA. In Docker, mount the bundle read-only and point both at that path.
# SSL_CERT_FILE=/absolute/path/to/corp-ca-bundle.pem
# REQUESTS_CA_BUNDLE=/absolute/path/to/corp-ca-bundle.pem

# ─── Proxy behavior (gateway + Xray + GitLab + step0 scripts) ────
# By DEFAULT the pipeline connects DIRECTLY and IGNORES the environment's
# HTTP_PROXY / HTTPS_PROXY / NO_PROXY variables — this covers the gateway (httpx)
# AND the Xray + GitLab clients (requests). Routing the request through an
# env-configured proxy is a common cause of "server disconnected without sending
# a response" even when the TLS/mTLS handshake succeeds (a direct `curl` works;
# the same request through the proxy drops). Opt back in ONLY if your gateway/Jira
# is reachable solely through a proxy — httpx and requests then honor
# HTTP(S)_PROXY/NO_PROXY:
# USE_HTTP_PROXY=true

# ─── LLM Gateway (OpenAI-compatible) ─────────────────────────────
# Required by: scripts/step0_verify_tool_calling.py, scripts/step0b_verify_embeddings.py
LLM_BASE_URL=https://your-internal-gateway/v1   # include trailing /v1 if your gateway uses it
LLM_API_KEY=                                    # paste secret here, never commit
PLANNER_MODEL=openai/gpt-oss-120b
GENERATOR_MODEL=mistralai/devstral-small-2-2512
HEALER_MODEL=openai/gpt-oss-120b
#
# Optional: run JUST the Planner against a DIFFERENT OpenAI-compatible endpoint than
# LLM_BASE_URL (e.g. a separately-hosted model). Every other agent still uses
# LLM_BASE_URL / LLM_API_KEY. Leave PLANNER_LLM_API_KEY blank for a keyless endpoint —
# the shared LLM_API_KEY is then never sent to the override. Unset = the Planner uses
# the shared gateway like the other agents.
# PLANNER_LLM_BASE_URL=https://another-endpoint/v1
# PLANNER_LLM_API_KEY=
# Optional reasoning effort for the browser agents (low | medium | high). Only meaningful
# on reasoning models (e.g. gpt-oss); never sent to the Generator. IMPORTANT: many
# OpenAI-compatible gateways silently DROP unknown request params — run
# scripts/step0d_verify_reasoning_effort.py first and only set these if it reports HONORED.
# PLANNER_REASONING_EFFORT=high
# HEALER_REASONING_EFFORT=medium
# TIP: if the Planner UNDER-EXPLORES (skips pages, jumps to code-gen too early) on a complex app,
# PLANNER_REASONING_EFFORT=high is the first knob to try (after step0d confirms it's HONORED).
#
# Per-request completion-token budget for the browser agents (Planner/Healer); unset = the
# provider's default. Set it (e.g. 8000) when a gateway applies a SMALL default max_tokens and a
# THINKING model's turn gets truncated: the response arrives thinking-only or cut mid-emission,
# pydantic-ai rejects and retries it, and the run dies of retry exhaustion ("exceeded maximum
# ... retries"). Requires the gateway to honor request-level max_tokens.
# AGENT_MAX_OUTPUT_TOKENS=8000

# ─── Vision Aid sensor for the Planner & Healer (optional, OFF by default) ─────
# RECOMMENDED for menu-driven / partly-inaccessible apps: vision lets the browser agents SEE the
# page when the accessibility snapshot is empty/sparse — so they re-orient instead of stalling or
# refusing "no interactive elements", and the locator->vision steer recovers them when stuck.
# When AGENT_VISION is a positive integer N, BOTH text-only browser agents (the Planner AND the
# Healer) gain an `inspect_screen` tool: it screenshots the page and asks the VISION-capable Vision
# Aid Agent to describe what is actually rendered (did a dropdown open? is a modal/overlay covering
# the page? did a success/error toast appear? is the button greyed out?) — useful when the
# accessibility snapshot is ambiguous. Every answer has two parts — "Answer:" (flags a wrong
# premise explicitly) and "On screen:" (what the page actually shows) — so even a disoriented
# agent asking the wrong question gets re-oriented. N caps the vision calls PER AGENT RUN — N per planning run
# AND N per heal attempt; each agent lifecycle starts fresh, so a test with 3 heal attempts may use
# up to 3xN total (by design — deep failure-path repro is not starved by an earlier run). `false` /
# `0` / unset disables it (both agents are then identical to before). REQUIRES a multimodal model on
# your gateway (VISION_MODEL). The sensor only DESCRIBES the page — it never produces selectors;
# targeting still goes through browser_generate_locator.
# AGENT_VISION=3
# VISION_MODEL=mistralai/devstral-small-2-2512
# inspect_screen captures the CURRENT page itself each time it runs, so its answer normally
# reflects the live page. This is a FALLBACK guard for the rare case that self-capture fails: it
# ignores an existing screenshot older than this many seconds (default 45) rather than describe an
# ancient leftover as current. Raise it only if that fallback bounces on a slow gateway.
# PLANNER_VISION_STALE_S=45
# When vision is on, each agent also gains a deterministic locator->vision steer: after this many
# CONSECUTIVE browser_generate_locator failures it stops retrying the same locator and is told to
# screenshot + inspect_screen and re-orient (repeated failures are usually a stale ref / wrong page /
# overlay, not a missing id). Default 3; clamped below AGENT_MCP_RETRIES so a retry remains to act on
# the steer. No effect when vision is off.
# PLANNER_LOCATOR_STEER_AFTER=3
# NOTE: the agents now fully execute flows (submit forms, create data, reproduce failure paths) — on
# a complex app this adds turns. If a run reports UsageLimitExceeded mid-heal, raise AGENT_REQUEST_LIMIT.

# ─── DOM Probe for the Planner & Healer (optional, OFF by default) ─────
# RECOMMENDED for barely-accessible apps (non-semantic div/span controls). The accessibility
# snapshot is the agents' only DOM view; on such apps it shows unnamed "generic" nodes, so an
# element can be visible yet unfindable — and the CSS/XPath rungs of the locator ladder have no
# data to author a candidate from. When AGENT_DOM_PROBE is a positive integer N, BOTH browser
# agents gain a read-only `probe_dom(text, scope?)` tool: it searches the live DOM for elements
# matching visible text/attributes and returns their real tag/id/classes/attributes plus
# CANDIDATE css/xpath selectors with match counts. Candidates are recon only — the agent still
# verifies via browser_generate_locator before recording anything. Implemented as ONE fixed,
# pipeline-authored JS function; the model only supplies the search text (it can never inject
# code), and the raw browser_evaluate tool stays hidden from the agents. N caps probe calls PER
# AGENT RUN (per planning run; per heal attempt). No extra model needed. `false`/`0`/unset
# disables it (prompts + toolset then byte-identical to before).
# AGENT_DOM_PROBE=10

# ─── Embedding + Rerank + retrieval memory (optional, for RAG) ─────
# Required by: scripts/step0b_verify_embeddings.py, src/ai_test_gen/rag/embeddings.py
# NOTE: confirm an embedding model is available on your gateway; if your app or its
# content is non-English, prefer a multilingual or matching-language variant.
EMBEDDING_MODEL=mxbai-embed-large
RERANKER_MODEL=zeroentropy/zerank-1-small       # bge-reranker-v2-m3 is the measured A/B alternative
RERANK_ENDPOINT=                                # optional: override if /rerank lives outside /v1
# Retrieval memory — an EMBEDDED (in-process, local-mode) knowledge base of solved
# test cases; a directory on disk, no server (rag/store.py). OFF by default: leave
# RAG_ENABLED unset/false and the pipeline is byte-identical (rag/ never imported).
# RAG_ENABLED=false
# KB_PATH=qdrant_storage                        # storage dir (gitignored); relative = repo root
# Offline KB seeding — regex that marks a corpus test for discovery; the default matches the
# Selenium suite's @Xray(testCase = "KEY") annotation and captures the linked key in group 1.
# Override for a different corpus/framework (the pattern MUST keep exactly one capturing group).
# TEST_MARKER_REGEX=@Xray\s*\(\s*testCase\s*=\s*"([^"]+)"\s*\)
# The Distiller/Mapper chat model that explores the corpus during offline seeding.
# Unset = follows GENERATOR_MODEL (a code-reading class); escalate to a reasoning model
# (e.g. openai/gpt-oss-120b) only if seeding review shows shallow reconstruction.
# DISTILLER_MODEL=
# Per-exploration tool-call budget for the seeding agents (suite Mapper now, per-test
# Distiller next) — how many read_file/search/list_dir round-trips one map or one test
# distillation may spend before the agent must produce its output. Default 40.
# DISTILLER_REQUEST_LIMIT=40

# ─── Jira / Xray ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Required by: scripts/step0c_xray_flavor.py, src/ai_test_gen/xray_client.py, scripts/test_xray.py
JIRA_BASE_URL=https://yourcompany.atlassian.net
JIRA_EMAIL=your.email@company.com               # Cloud: account email; Server/DC: username
JIRA_TOKEN=                                     # Cloud: API token from id.atlassian.com; Server/DC: PAT (sent as Bearer) or password
XRAY_IS_CLOUD=true                              # true for *.atlassian.net, false for self-hosted Jira
# Server/DC only: custom field holding the manual test steps. A common default is
# customfield_11006 ("Manual Test Steps"); find yours with
# scripts/step0c_xray_flavor.py --issue-key <KEY>. Leave unset to use the default.
# XRAY_STEPS_FIELD_ID=customfield_11006

# ─── Test-case source: xray (default) or local JSON ──────────────
# Consumed by: src/ai_test_gen/config.py (load_config) + the orchestrator.
# "xray" (default) fetches each case live from the Jira/Xray tenant above (JIRA_* required).
# "local" reads raw-Xray-shaped JSON from LOCAL_TESTCASE_DIR instead — NO Jira tenant, so
# JIRA_* become optional. The CLI arg is the file stem: `run_one.py NOTE-2` loads
# <LOCAL_TESTCASE_DIR>/NOTE-2.json. Relative paths resolve from the repo root.
# TESTCASE_SOURCE=xray
# LOCAL_TESTCASE_DIR=packages/demo-notes-app/test-cases   # required when TESTCASE_SOURCE=local
#
# The human-authored context files default to ./project_context.md and ./project_map.md, but
# can point elsewhere so a different app under test can ship its own committed context:
# PROJECT_CONTEXT_PATH=packages/demo-notes-app/project_context.md
# PROJECT_MAP_PATH=packages/demo-notes-app/project_map.md
#
# DEMO PROFILE — run the pipeline against the bundled demo app with zero Jira/GitLab:
#   1) cd packages/demo-notes-app && npm install && npm run dev   # serves http://localhost:3000
#   2) uncomment the six lines below, then: uv run python scripts/run_one.py NOTE-2 --verbose
#   (You still need a working model gateway: LLM_BASE_URL / LLM_API_KEY above.)
# TESTCASE_SOURCE=local
# LOCAL_TESTCASE_DIR=packages/demo-notes-app/test-cases
# PROJECT_CONTEXT_PATH=packages/demo-notes-app/project_context.md
# PROJECT_MAP_PATH=packages/demo-notes-app/project_map.md
# STAGING_BASE_URL=http://localhost:3000
# GITLAB_ENABLED=false

# ─── Staging app under test ──────────────────────────────────────
# Required by: src/ai_test_gen/config.py (load_config); manual smoke check
# GUARDRAIL: STAGING_BASE_URL's host must contain a non-prod marker (see next
# section) or load_config() HARD-FAILS. The pipeline drives a real browser and
# runs generated tests against this URL — staging only, never production.
STAGING_BASE_URL=https://staging.yourapp.internal
# OPTIONAL / legacy: only scripts/save_auth_state.py (manual session capture) reads
# these. The pipeline itself logs in with the test users from project_context.md.
# STAGING_USERNAME=qa.bot
# STAGING_PASSWORD=

# ─── Production-URL guardrail (fail-closed allow-list) ───────────
# Consumed by: src/ai_test_gen/config.py (load_config)
# load_config() refuses to start unless STAGING_BASE_URL's host contains one of
# these case-insensitive substrings. Built-in defaults (no need to repeat them):
# localhost, 127.0.0.1, staging, qa, demo. If your lower environments use other
# tokens (e.g. uat, sandbox, int), list them below — comma-separated — and they
# are MERGED with the defaults. Leave unset to use the defaults only.
# NON_PROD_URL_MARKERS=uat,sandbox

# ─── GitLab (MR destination) ────────────────
# Required by: manual smoke check (curl with PRIVATE-TOKEN header)
# GITLAB_ENABLED=false runs the pipeline WITHOUT GitLab: it skips the MR step and the
# three GITLAB_* vars below are NOT required (handy for local Docker runs — the test +
# plan are still written to output/). Default true: the MR is opened and GITLAB_* must
# be set.
# GITLAB_ENABLED=true
GITLAB_BASE_URL=https://gitlab.yourcompany.internal
GITLAB_TOKEN=                                   # PAT with `api` scope, OR project access token with Developer + write_repository
GITLAB_PROJECT_ID=qa/playwright-tests           # "group/project" path or numeric ID
GITLAB_TARGET_BRANCH=main

# ─── Orchestrator ────────────────────────────────────
# Consumed by: src/ai_test_gen/orchestrator.py
# Each run writes a log to output/runs/run-<key>-<timestamp>.log (path printed at start + end).
# Default INFO captures every step + every failure (incl. the gateway's error body, logged at
# WARNING/ERROR) without replaying the agents' conversations, so it stays small. Set DEBUG only
# for a deeper dive. --verbose raises CONSOLE verbosity only; it does not change the file.
# RUN_LOG_LEVEL=INFO
# Max Healer attempts before the MR is opened for review anyway (default 3). The default leaves
# room for locator-kind escalation: when the same step keeps failing, the Healer descends the
# resilience ladder (id → accessible → CSS → XPath) instead of re-trying the same locator.
# A heal attempt that CRASHES (agent/gateway/MCP exception) consumes its attempt and healing
# CONTINUES with a fresh Healer; only 2 consecutive crashed attempts stop the loop early, so a
# large budget here (e.g. 15) is actually honored.
# MAX_HEAL_ATTEMPTS=3
# Max retries for the browser agents (Planner/Healer) when an MCP tool errors while hunting
# selectors. NOTE this is a DIFFERENT knob than MAX_HEAL_ATTEMPTS: it caps tool-error retries
# WITHIN one agent run ("exceeded max retries count of N" in a log names this one). For
# browser_generate_locator the run no longer dies at this ceiling — the agent is told to give up
# on that element (descend the ladder / probe_dom / note the gap) and continue. Default 5.
# AGENT_MCP_RETRIES=5
# Structured-output retry budget (a DIFFERENT knob again): retries for the MODEL'S OWN responses
# — empty turns, unparsed tool calls, output-schema validation failures ("Exceeded maximum output
# retries" names this one). These accumulate CUMULATIVELY across a run (successful turns don't
# reset the counter), so a gateway whose tool-call parsing is intermittently flaky can kill a
# long exploration even though every single bounce is recoverable. Default 15;
# AGENT_REQUEST_LIMIT stays the hard backstop on total run size.
# AGENT_OUTPUT_RETRIES=15
# Max model requests per browser-agent run (pydantic-ai request_limit). Exploring a multi-step
# flow makes many round-trips; the library default of 50 aborts mid-run ("UsageLimitExceeded").
# Default 300; raise for very long flows, lower to cap cost.
# AGENT_REQUEST_LIMIT=300
# EXPERIMENTAL — browser-agent history trimming (DISABLED by default).
# Every MCP browser tool result embeds a full accessibility snapshot; trimming was
# built to cut that replay cost, but live runs showed mid-tier reasoning models
# losing coherence with it enabled (early give-up, skipped pages, fabricated plan
# steps). Leave both unset for normal runs; set them only for a controlled A/B.
# - SNAPSHOT_HISTORY_KEEP: set to a number to ENABLE trimming — that many newest
#   snapshots stay verbatim, the rest are stubbed.
# - ANCHOR_SNAPSHOTS (only meaningful when trimming is enabled; default on): also
#   keeps the latest snapshot of every page where a locator was captured (deduped
#   per URL + dialog-open state). off = pure newest-N window.
# SNAPSHOT_HISTORY_KEEP=2
# ANCHOR_SNAPSHOTS=on

# ─── Playwright MCP toggles (debug) ──────────────────────────────
# Consumed by: src/ai_test_gen/playwright_mcp.py
# Watch the browser drive (headed) while debugging the Planner/Healer:
# PLAYWRIGHT_MCP_HEADED=true
#
# NOT env toggles: verified-selector capture and treating the app's id= as the test id are
# committed in playwright-mcp-config.json ("capabilities": ["testing"], "testIdAttribute": "id")
# and mirrored in output/playwright.config.ts (use.testIdAttribute='id').

# ─── Test-user credentials are NOT here ──────────────────────────
# The dummy staging *user* logins that generated tests sign in with live in
# project_context.md §3 (Test users), NOT in .env — see project_context.example.md.
# Generated .spec.ts embed those disposable dummy creds directly. .env holds only
# infra secrets (gateway, Jira/Xray, GitLab, staging URL, mTLS).
